getMae <- function(maxdepth, trainData, testData) {
    print(maxdepth)
    model <- rpart(
        formula = Price ~ .,
        data    = trainData,
        method  = "anova",
        control = list(maxdepth = maxdepth)
    )
    rpart.plot(model)
    
    pred_train <- predict(model, trainData)
    mae_train <- MAE(pred_train, trainData$Price)
    
    pred_test <- predict(model, testData)
    mae_test <- MAE(pred_test, testData$Price)
    return(c(mae_train,mae_test ))
} 
num <- 1:10

Data Cleaning

1. Scaling and Normalization

Scaling

MinMax Scaler

set.seed(42)
original_data <- rexp(n = 1000,rate=1/100)

# min-max scale data between 0 and 1
scaled_data <- (original_data - min(original_data))/ (max(original_data) - min(original_data))

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
hist(original_data)
hist(scaled_data)

# Notice that the shape of the data doesn't change, but that instead of ranging from 0 to 8ish, it now ranges from 0 to 1.

Normalization/Standard Scaler

Z-score Normalization

normalized_data <- scale(original_data)
normalized_data2 <- (original_data - mean(original_data))/sd(original_data)
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
hist(original_data)
hist(normalized_data)
